body:
@potiuk, thanks for confirming. No worry, i just wanted to make sure this is expected, not due to some kind of bug :)

Usually I would recommend not doing any kind of force push to master (or to any other permanent public branches) since it will cause conflict to downstream contributors. In our case, it broke our internal git mirroring.

I also recommend setting master to a protected branch on github so it won't get force updated with wrong history accidentally. I have done this in the past and it was not a fun exercise to communicate and revert ;)
